  + [next_question] is which alignment/depletion condition is known to imply regularity and whether it can be propagated

& [Candidate_005_CriticalSmallness] is a matrix row
  + [candidate_control] is small data in critical spaces
  + [controlled_quantity] is critical norm initially and through evolution
  + [regularity_criterion_contact] is global regularity for sufficiently small critical data
  + [scaling_status] is critical_but_small_data
  + [anti_concentration_job] is prevents nonlinear cascade from becoming large
  + [known_boundary] is known_special_case_not_large_data_solution
  + [symbolic_fit] is resonance anchor as initial controlled amplitude
  + [next_question] is not enough for Clay large smooth data unless a mechanism creates effective smallness

& [MatrixFinding] is the current conclusion
  + [best_formal_pressure] is critical norm control and vorticity/strain continuation criteria
  + [best_symbolic_fit] is strain/alignment geometry as phase correction and depletion of nonlinearity
  + [weakest_candidate] is basic energy inequality because it dissipates but does not control critical concentration
  + [shape_correction] is surface tension must mean critical anti-concentration, not generic smoothing
  + [proposition_update] is the source document's Navier-Stokes approach becomes proof-relevant only if phase correction can be formalized as a propagated geometric depletion or critical norm control mechanism

